Even in his graver work, such as the Fasti, he plays lightly with his task, and finds food for merriment in the exploits of gods and goddesses. We may suppose that his choice of the elegiac as his favourite metro was determined by its fitness for neat and witty turns, without the necessity for sustained effort, and by his fondness for rhetorical expression, which must have been fostered by his early training.
